    seoTitle: "Basic Metabolic Panel – MLT Encyclopedia", seoDescription: "BMP components, reference ranges, and clinical interpretation for MLT exam. Covers sodium, potassium, chloride, CO2, glucose, BUN, creatinine, calcium.", seoKeywords: ["basic metabolic panel", "BMP", "electrolytes", "glucose", "BUN", "creatinine", "MLT exam"],
    overview: "The Basic Metabolic Panel (BMP) is an 8-test chemistry panel measuring sodium, potassium, chloride, CO2 (bicarbonate), glucose, blood urea nitrogen (BUN), creatinine, and calcium. It provides essential information about electrolyte balance, acid-base status, kidney function, and glucose metabolism. The BMP is one of the most frequently ordered laboratory panels and requires a serum or lithium heparin plasma specimen.",
    mechanismPhysiology: "Electrolytes maintain osmotic pressure, acid-base balance, and membrane potentials. Sodium is the primary extracellular cation regulated by aldosterone and ADH. Potassium is the primary intracellular cation critical for cardiac conduction. Chloride follows sodium passively. Bicarbonate (CO2) reflects the metabolic component of acid-base balance. Glucose is regulated by insulin and glucagon. BUN and creatinine reflect glomerular filtration rate (GFR).",
    clinicalRelevance: "Critical values requiring immediate notification: potassium <3.0 or >6.0 mEq/L (cardiac arrhythmia risk), sodium <120 or >160 mEq/L, glucose <40 or >500 mg/dL, calcium <6.0 or >13.0 mg/dL. The anion gap (Na - Cl - CO2) normal is 8-12 mEq/L; elevation suggests metabolic acidosis (DKA, lactic acidosis, renal failure, toxins).",
    signsSymptoms: "Hyponatremia: confusion, seizures. Hyperkalemia: cardiac arrhythmias, muscle weakness. Hypoglycemia: sweating, tremor, confusion. Elevated BUN/creatinine: uremia, fatigue, nausea. Hypercalcemia: confusion, polyuria, constipation.",
    assessment: "Specimen: serum (SST/gold top) or lithium heparin plasma (green top). Hemolysis falsely elevates potassium (most common pre-analytical error). Fasting specimen required for glucose. Ion-selective electrodes (ISE) measure Na, K, Cl using direct or indirect methods. Enzymatic methods measure glucose, BUN, creatinine. Arsenazo III method for calcium.",
    management: "Abnormal results guide fluid management, electrolyte replacement, insulin therapy, and renal function assessment. Serial BMPs monitor treatment response. Critical values require immediate physician notification per laboratory protocol.",
    complications: "Hemolysis is the most common pre-analytical error, falsely elevating potassium and LDH. Delayed separation of serum from cells increases potassium (cellular leakage). Heparin contamination from line draws can interfere with calcium results. IV fluid contamination can dilute all analytes.",
    clinicalPearls: ["Hemolysis increases potassium by approximately 0.6 mEq/L for each 100 mg/dL of free hemoglobin", "The anion gap = Na - (Cl + CO2); normal 8-12 mEq/L; mnemonic MUDPILES for elevated anion gap causes", "Ionized calcium is the physiologically active form—total calcium is affected by albumin levels"],
    examPitfalls: ["Hemolyzed specimens have FALSELY ELEVATED potassium—always check the hemolysis index", "Indirect ISE methods are affected by abnormal protein/lipid levels (pseudohyponatremia); direct ISE methods are not", "BUN is affected by protein intake and hydration status; creatinine is a better marker of GFR"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "What causes pseudohyponatremia?", answer: "Severely elevated lipids or proteins (as in multiple myeloma) reduce the water fraction of the sample, causing falsely low sodium by indirect ISE methods. Direct ISE and blood gas analyzers give accurate results." }, { question: "What is the anion gap?", answer: "Calculated as Na - (Cl + CO2). Normal is 8-12 mEq/L. An elevated anion gap indicates unmeasured anions (lactate, ketones, uremic toxins, drug metabolites) causing metabolic acidosis." }, { question: "Why is potassium the most commonly hemolysis-affected analyte?", answer: "RBCs contain approximately 23× more potassium than serum. Even mild hemolysis releases intracellular potassium, causing clinically significant false elevation." }],
