    overview: "Liver function tests (LFTs) encompass enzymes and proteins that assess hepatocellular injury, cholestasis, and synthetic function. Key analytes include AST (aspartate aminotransferase), ALT (alanine aminotransferase), ALP (alkaline phosphatase), GGT (gamma-glutamyl transferase), total and direct bilirubin, albumin, and total protein. Pattern recognition distinguishes hepatocellular damage (elevated AST/ALT) from cholestatic disease (elevated ALP/GGT).",
    mechanismPhysiology: "ALT is primarily found in the liver (hepatocyte cytoplasm), making it more specific for liver injury. AST is found in liver, heart, skeletal muscle, and other tissues (both cytoplasm and mitochondria). ALP is present in bile duct epithelium, bone, intestine, and placenta. GGT is found in bile duct epithelium and is induced by alcohol and drugs. Bilirubin is the breakdown product of heme: unconjugated (indirect) bilirubin is transported to the liver, conjugated (direct) by glucuronyl transferase, and excreted in bile.",
    clinicalRelevance: "Hepatocellular pattern: ALT > AST (most liver diseases); AST > ALT (alcoholic liver disease—De Ritis ratio >2). Cholestatic pattern: elevated ALP and GGT with mild AST/ALT elevation. Elevated ALP with normal GGT suggests bone origin. Elevated indirect bilirubin: hemolysis, Gilbert syndrome. Elevated direct bilirubin: obstructive jaundice, hepatitis. Decreased albumin indicates impaired hepatic synthetic function.",
