    examPitfalls: ["ALT is more SPECIFIC for liver than AST—AST is found in many tissues", "ALP is elevated in both liver disease AND bone disease—GGT differentiates them", "Direct bilirubin reacts WITHOUT accelerator in the Jendrassik-Grof method"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "What is the De Ritis ratio?", answer: "The AST:ALT ratio. A ratio >2 is characteristic of alcoholic liver disease. In most other liver diseases, ALT exceeds AST (ratio <1)." }, { question: "How do you determine if elevated ALP is from liver or bone?", answer: "If GGT is also elevated, the source is likely hepatobiliary. If GGT is normal, the source is likely bone. ALP isoenzyme electrophoresis can also differentiate the source." }, { question: "What is the difference between direct and indirect bilirubin?", answer: "Direct (conjugated) bilirubin has been processed by the liver and is water-soluble. Indirect (unconjugated) bilirubin has not yet been conjugated and is lipid-soluble, bound to albumin in blood." }],
