  {
    profession: "mlt", slug: "cerebrospinal-fluid-analysis", title: "Cerebrospinal Fluid (CSF) Analysis", category: "Body Fluids",
    seoTitle: "CSF Analysis – MLT Encyclopedia", seoDescription: "Cerebrospinal fluid analysis: cell count, protein, glucose, Gram stain, and differential diagnosis of meningitis for MLT exam preparation.", seoKeywords: ["CSF analysis", "cerebrospinal fluid", "meningitis", "CSF cell count", "CSF protein", "CSF glucose", "MLT exam"],
    overview: "Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) analysis is a critical STAT procedure for diagnosing meningitis, encephalitis, subarachnoid hemorrhage, and other CNS conditions. The standard CSF examination includes appearance (clarity, color), cell count and differential, protein, glucose (compared to serum glucose), Gram stain, and culture. CSF specimens are irreplaceable and must be processed IMMEDIATELY. Three tubes are typically collected: tube 1 (chemistry/serology), tube 2 (microbiology), tube 3 (cell count/differential).",
    mechanismPhysiology: "CSF is produced by the choroid plexus at ~20 mL/hour (total volume 90-150 mL in adults). Normal CSF is crystal clear, colorless, with glucose 60-70% of serum glucose, protein 15-45 mg/dL, and 0-5 WBC/μL (all mononuclear cells). In bacterial meningitis: neutrophilic pleocytosis (WBC 1000-5000+/μL), decreased glucose (<40 mg/dL or <40% of serum), elevated protein (>100 mg/dL). In viral meningitis: lymphocytic pleocytosis (WBC 25-500/μL), normal glucose, mildly elevated protein.",
    clinicalRelevance: "Bacterial meningitis: medical emergency—Gram stain and culture are critical. Common pathogens: Neisseria meningitidis (Gram-negative diplococci), Streptococcus pneumoniae (Gram-positive diplococci), Haemophilus influenzae (Gram-negative coccobacilli), Group B Strep (neonates), Listeria (neonates, elderly). Viral meningitis: enterovirus most common. Fungal meningitis: Cryptococcus neoformans (India ink, CrAg test). TB meningitis: acid-fast smear, mycobacterial culture.",
    signsSymptoms: "Meningitis: headache, neck stiffness (nuchal rigidity), fever, photophobia, altered mental status, Kernig sign, Brudzinski sign. Neonates: fever, irritability, poor feeding, bulging fontanelle.",
    assessment: "Appearance: crystal clear (normal), turbid/cloudy (bacterial meningitis—WBC >200/μL causes turbidity), xanthochromic (yellow—subarachnoid hemorrhage >2 hours or very high protein). Cell count: manual hemacytometer (Neubauer chamber), count all cells in undiluted CSF. Differential: cytocentrifuge preparation (Cytospin), Wright-Giemsa stain. Gram stain: positive in 60-90% of bacterial meningitis. Culture: blood agar, chocolate agar (CO2), thioglycolate broth. Rapid tests: latex agglutination, CrAg, PCR panels (FilmArray Meningitis/Encephalitis panel).",
    management: "CSF is a STAT specimen—process IMMEDIATELY. Never refrigerate CSF for culture (N. meningitidis and H. influenzae are cold-sensitive). Use tube 3 for cell count (least likely to be contaminated by traumatic tap). If traumatic tap suspected: compare tube 1 and tube 3 RBC counts—decreasing count suggests traumatic tap; consistent count suggests true subarachnoid hemorrhage.",
    complications: "Traumatic tap introduces blood into CSF, complicating interpretation. Correction for traumatic tap: subtract 1 WBC per 700-1000 RBCs. Xanthochromia (yellow supernatant) distinguishes true subarachnoid hemorrhage from traumatic tap—xanthochromia appears >2 hours after hemorrhage. Delayed processing degrades cells and glucose, producing unreliable results.",
    clinicalPearls: ["CSF is IRREPLACEABLE and must be processed IMMEDIATELY—it is the highest priority specimen in the lab", "Normal CSF glucose is 60-70% of SERUM glucose—always compare to a simultaneous blood glucose", "Tube 3 is used for cell count because it is least likely to contain cells from traumatic tap contamination"],
    examPitfalls: ["Never REFRIGERATE CSF for culture—N. meningitidis and H. influenzae are COLD-SENSITIVE", "Xanthochromia (yellow CSF) indicates subarachnoid hemorrhage >2 hours old; traumatic tap CSF clears in successive tubes", "CSF glucose is LOW in bacterial and fungal meningitis but NORMAL in most viral meningitis"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "How do you differentiate bacterial from viral meningitis by CSF findings?", answer: "Bacterial: WBC 1000-5000+/μL (neutrophil predominance), glucose <40 mg/dL (<40% serum), protein >100 mg/dL, positive Gram stain/culture. Viral: WBC 25-500/μL (lymphocyte predominance), normal glucose, mildly elevated protein, negative Gram stain." }, { question: "What is xanthochromia?", answer: "Yellow discoloration of CSF caused by breakdown of RBC hemoglobin to bilirubin, indicating subarachnoid hemorrhage that occurred at least 2 hours prior. It distinguishes true hemorrhage from traumatic tap (which produces bloody but not xanthochromic CSF)." }, { question: "Why is tube 3 used for cell count?", answer: "In a traumatic tap, tubes collected first (tube 1) have more blood contamination than tubes collected later (tube 3). Using tube 3 provides a more accurate cell count representative of the true CSF, not the iatrogenic blood contamination." }],
    relatedLessonIds: [], relatedQuestionIds: ["Body Fluids"], status: "published"
  },
  {
    profession: "mlt", slug: "synovial-fluid-analysis", title: "Synovial Fluid Analysis", category: "Body Fluids",
    seoTitle: "Synovial Fluid Analysis – MLT Encyclopedia", seoDescription: "Synovial fluid analysis: crystal identification, cell count, and classification of joint effusions for medical laboratory technologist exam.", seoKeywords: ["synovial fluid", "crystal analysis", "gout", "pseudogout", "monosodium urate", "CPPD", "MLT exam"],
    overview: "Synovial fluid analysis is essential for diagnosing joint disorders including crystal-induced arthritis (gout, pseudogout), septic arthritis, and inflammatory arthritis. The analysis includes gross appearance, viscosity, WBC count and differential, crystal identification using compensated polarized microscopy, Gram stain, and culture. Crystal identification is one of the most important procedures—monosodium urate (MSU) crystals indicate gout while calcium pyrophosphate dihydrate (CPPD) crystals indicate pseudogout.",
    mechanismPhysiology: "Normal synovial fluid is viscous (due to hyaluronic acid), clear, pale yellow, with <200 WBC/μL (mostly mononuclear). Joint effusion classification: Group I (non-inflammatory): clear, high viscosity, WBC <2000 (osteoarthritis). Group II (inflammatory): translucent/cloudy, decreased viscosity, WBC 2000-75,000 with neutrophil predominance (RA, gout, pseudogout). Group III (septic): opaque/purulent, very low viscosity, WBC >50,000-100,000+ with >90% neutrophils (bacterial infection). Group IV (hemorrhagic): bloody (trauma, hemophilia, tumor).",
    clinicalRelevance: "Gout: MSU crystals are needle-shaped, strongly NEGATIVELY birefringent under compensated polarized light (yellow when parallel to slow vibration axis of compensator). Pseudogout: CPPD crystals are rhomboid/rod-shaped, WEAKLY POSITIVELY birefringent (blue when parallel to compensator). Septic arthritis: WBC >50,000 with >90% PMNs, positive Gram stain/culture—medical emergency requiring joint drainage and antibiotics.",
    signsSymptoms: "Gout: acute onset monoarthritis (classically first MTP joint—podagra), severe pain, redness, swelling. Pseudogout: acute or chronic arthritis, commonly affects knees and wrists. Septic arthritis: hot, red, swollen joint with fever and severe pain.",
    assessment: "Gross exam: color, clarity, viscosity (string test—normal fluid forms a 4-6 cm string). WBC count: hemacytometer with saline diluent (NOT acetic acid, which clots hyaluronic acid and forms a mucin clot). Crystal identification: wet mount under compensated polarized microscopy with a first-order red compensator. Gram stain and culture: rule out septic arthritis. Mucin clot test (historical): add acetic acid to fluid—good clot = non-inflammatory; poor/friable clot = inflammatory.",
    management: "STAT crystal examination when gout or pseudogout is suspected. Report crystal type, birefringence (negative or positive), and whether intracellular (inside neutrophils) or extracellular. Intracellular crystals indicate active crystal-induced inflammation. Report cell count, differential, and culture results.",
    complications: "Improper use of polarizing microscope leads to misidentification of crystals. Oxalate anticoagulant can form crystals that mimic CPPD—use heparin or EDTA tubes. Corticosteroid crystals from previous joint injection may be present and can be confused with MSU/CPPD. Bloody fluid requires correction of WBC count for RBC contamination.",
    clinicalPearls: ["MSU crystals (gout) are NEGATIVELY birefringent—YELLOW when PARALLEL to the compensator axis (remember: Yellow = Negative = Gout)", "CPPD crystals (pseudogout) are POSITIVELY birefringent—BLUE when PARALLEL to the compensator axis", "Do NOT use ACETIC ACID as diluent for synovial fluid cell counts—it causes the mucin clot to form and trap cells"],
    examPitfalls: ["Negative birefringence (MSU/gout) = YELLOW parallel to compensator; Positive birefringence (CPPD/pseudogout) = BLUE parallel", "Use SALINE or hypotonic saline as diluent for synovial fluid cell counts, NEVER acetic acid", "Intracellular crystals (inside neutrophils) indicate ACTIVE crystal-induced arthritis—extracellular crystals alone may represent chronic disease"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "How do you differentiate gout from pseudogout crystals?", answer: "Gout (MSU): needle-shaped, strongly negatively birefringent (yellow when parallel to compensator). Pseudogout (CPPD): rhomboid/rod-shaped, weakly positively birefringent (blue when parallel to compensator)." }, { question: "Why can't acetic acid be used for synovial fluid cell counts?", answer: "Acetic acid causes hyaluronic acid in synovial fluid to form a mucin clot, which traps WBCs and produces inaccurate (falsely low) cell counts. Use saline or hypotonic saline instead." }, { question: "What cell count suggests septic arthritis?", answer: "WBC >50,000/μL with >90% neutrophils strongly suggests septic (bacterial) arthritis. However, crystal-induced arthritis can occasionally produce similarly high counts—Gram stain and culture are essential." }],
    relatedLessonIds: [], relatedQuestionIds: ["Body Fluids"], status: "published"
  },
  // =================== MYCOLOGY (5 topics) ===================
  {
    profession: "mlt", slug: "dermatophyte-identification", title: "Dermatophyte Identification", category: "Mycology",
    seoTitle: "Dermatophyte Identification – MLT Encyclopedia", seoDescription: "Dermatophyte identification: Trichophyton, Microsporum, Epidermophyton. KOH prep, DTM, and macroconidia/microconidia morphology for MLT exam.", seoKeywords: ["dermatophytes", "Trichophyton", "Microsporum", "Epidermophyton", "ringworm", "DTM", "KOH prep", "MLT exam"],
    overview: "Dermatophytes are a group of closely related fungi that infect keratinized tissue (skin, hair, nails) and are the most common cause of superficial mycoses worldwide. The three genera are Trichophyton (infects skin, hair, and nails), Microsporum (infects skin and hair, NOT nails), and Epidermophyton (infects skin and nails, NOT hair). Identification relies on colony morphology, pigmentation, macroconidia and microconidia morphology, and special tests (urease, hair perforation, nutritional requirements).",
    mechanismPhysiology: "Dermatophytes produce keratinases that digest keratin, allowing invasion of the stratum corneum, hair shafts, and nail plates. Infections are named by body site: tinea capitis (scalp), tinea corporis (body/ringworm), tinea pedis (athlete's foot), tinea cruris (groin/jock itch), tinea unguium (onychomycosis/nails), tinea versicolor (actually caused by Malassezia, not a true dermatophyte). Transmission is through direct contact with infected humans (anthropophilic), animals (zoophilic), or soil (geophilic).",
    clinicalRelevance: "T. rubrum: most common dermatophyte worldwide—causes chronic tinea pedis, tinea corporis, and onychomycosis. T. tonsurans: most common cause of tinea capitis in North America. M. canis: zoophilic (from cats/dogs), causes tinea capitis and corporis, fluoresces yellow-green under Wood's lamp. E. floccosum: causes tinea cruris and tinea pedis—produces ONLY macroconidia (no microconidia).",
    signsSymptoms: "Circular, scaly, erythematous lesions with raised borders and central clearing (ringworm). Tinea capitis: hair loss, black dots (endothrix), scaling. Tinea pedis: interdigital maceration, scaling of soles. Onychomycosis: thickened, discolored, brittle nails.",
    assessment: "KOH preparation: 10-20% KOH dissolves keratin, revealing septate hyphae and arthrospores. Specimen: skin scrapings (active border), hair (plucked, not cut), nail clippings (subungual debris). Culture: Sabouraud dextrose agar (SDA) with cycloheximide + chloramphenicol or dermatophyte test medium (DTM). DTM turns red (alkaline) with dermatophyte growth but also with some saprophytes if read after 14 days. Examine macroconidia: Microsporum (thick-walled, rough, spindle-shaped), Trichophyton (thin-walled, smooth, pencil-shaped), Epidermophyton (club/beaver-tail shaped, smooth).",
    management: "Topical antifungals for localized skin infections. Oral antifungals (terbinafine, itraconazole, griseofulvin) for tinea capitis, onychomycosis, and extensive infections. Treatment duration: skin 2-4 weeks, nails 6-12 weeks (fingernails) to 12-24 weeks (toenails).",
    complications: "Dermatophyte culture requires 2-4 weeks for growth—patience needed. DTM should be read at 14 days maximum—saprophytes can cause false-positive color change after 14 days. KOH prep can be negative if specimen is collected from the wrong area (center of lesion vs active border).",
    clinicalPearls: ["Epidermophyton floccosum produces ONLY macroconidia (club/beaver-tail shaped)—no microconidia", "Microsporum canis fluoresces YELLOW-GREEN under Wood's lamp; most Trichophyton species do NOT fluoresce", "DTM should be read at 14 DAYS maximum—after that, saprophytes can produce false-positive alkaline (red) color change"],
    examPitfalls: ["Microsporum infects skin and HAIR but NOT nails; Epidermophyton infects skin and NAILS but NOT hair", "Trichophyton is the ONLY genus that infects ALL three keratinized tissues (skin, hair, AND nails)", "Wood's lamp examination is useful for Microsporum species but NOT for Trichophyton tonsurans (the most common tinea capitis agent in N. America does NOT fluoresce)"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "What are the three genera of dermatophytes?", answer: "Trichophyton (skin, hair, nails), Microsporum (skin, hair, NOT nails), Epidermophyton (skin, nails, NOT hair). Trichophyton is the only genus infecting all three keratinized tissues." }, { question: "What is the dermatophyte test medium (DTM)?", answer: "A selective culture medium containing phenol red indicator that changes from yellow to red (alkaline) when dermatophytes grow and metabolize proteins. Read at 14 days maximum—saprophytes can cause false positives if incubated longer." }, { question: "How do you differentiate the genera by macroconidia?", answer: "Microsporum: large, thick-walled, rough/echinulate, spindle-shaped. Trichophyton: thin-walled, smooth, pencil/cigar-shaped (rare). Epidermophyton: smooth, club/beaver-tail shaped, in clusters (no microconidia produced)." }],
    relatedLessonIds: [], relatedQuestionIds: ["Microbiology"], status: "published"
  }
